To recap some basics of the claims here:

Copyrights: the person who creates an image (e.g., by taking a photo) automatically owns the rights to that image. 

Except under limited circumstances, reproducing an image, especially for commercial purposes, without the creator's permission is copyright infringement.

And if they register the work with the Copyright Office within a certain timeframe, they can sue for statutory damages.

Publicity rights: everyone—not just models and celebrities—has the right to commercially exploit their own image and likeness. 

If someone else uses a picture of you without your permission for a commercial purpose, they have violated your right of publicity. 

That’s true even if the image is already publicly available.

“$20.00 (60% OFF) - WAS $50.00.”
 
Markdowns with slashed former prices like this are a common and effective sales tactic.

But if that $20.00 item was never actually offered at the $50.00 reference price of a substantial amount of time, the “sale” ad is illegal.

Using fake reference prices to run sales is illegal under both the FTC Act and California state laws.

The FTC rule says the former price needs to be “the actual, bona fide price at which the article was offered to the public on a regular basis for a reasonably substantial period of time.”

California’s law says the former price needs to have been “the prevailing market price” within three months before the sale ads run.

Class actions over these laws have been common for years and aren’t going away.

Here are a few settlement and judgment figures from lawsuits about this issue:

-Rougvie v. Ascena Retail Group - $50.8M (2016)

-Gattinella v. Kors - $4.8M (2016)

-Spann v. J.C. Penney - $50M (2016)

-People of the State of California v. Amazon.com - $2M (2021)

 -Khan v. Boohoo.com - $32.5M (2022)

There is no one-size-fits-all, clear-cut playbook for complying with all federal and state laws that cover this issue, or at least not one that I could try to fit into one post.

But generally, if you run a sale, make sure you first sell the products at the regular or original price for a period of time before marking them down, be sure you can support any claims you make, and periodically review your ads to make sure you are in compliance.

The models claimed that the club used their images to make it appear that they worked at, endorsed, or were otherwise affiliated with the club.

The claims involve the models' right of publicity, which is an issue that comes up over and over again in social media advertising. 

Your right of publicity protects against use of your name or likeness in an ad without your permission. 

And at least in California, you don't have to be a model or celebrity—everyone has a statutory right to recover for violations of their publicity rights.

This case is a good reminder that you cannot assume a model will be grateful for the exposure or give you permission after the fact if you use their images in your ads. 

If you use someone's picture to sell or promote a product or service, you must have their permission beforehand.
